    <!-- ═══════════════ BLOG CONTENT ═══════════════ -->
    <article class="blog-article">

        <!-- Kicker -->
        <p class="blog-kicker">System Design <span>·</span> Distributed Systems</p>

        <!-- Headline -->
        <h1 class="blog-headline">The Single Source of Truth<br>in Parallel Systems</h1>

        <!-- Subhead -->
        <p class="blog-subhead">
            When multiple services write to the same data concurrently, the question
            isn't who is fastest — it's who gets to be right.
        </p>

        <!-- Meta -->
        <div class="blog-meta">
            <span>8 min read</span>
            <span>SSOT</span>
            <span>Concurrency</span>
            <span>Event Sourcing</span>
            <span>May 2026</span>
        </div>

        <!-- Body -->
        <div class="blog-body">

            <p>
                Parallelism is one of the great gifts of modern distributed systems. Spin up ten
                workers, crunch ten times the data — in theory. In practice, parallel operations
                that share mutable state produce a special kind of chaos: race conditions,
                split-brain scenarios, and the most insidious bug of all, a system that looks
                consistent from the outside while quietly lying to everyone.
            </p>
            <p>
                The <strong>Single Source of Truth (SSOT)</strong> pattern is the antidote. It is the
                architectural discipline of designating exactly one authoritative location for each
                piece of state, and routing every read and write through that location. In the context
                of parallel operations, it transforms an inherently competitive problem — many writers,
                one truth — into a tractable engineering challenge.
            </p>

            <div class="section-accent"></div>

            <!-- Section 1 -->
            <h2>Why parallel systems drift apart</h2>
            <p>
                Imagine a distributed inventory system. Three services are reconciling stock counts
                in parallel: an e-commerce checkout, a warehouse management system, and a returns
                processor. Each has a local view of the item count. Each updates its view concurrently.
                Without a single authority, you get conflicting realities:
            </p>

            <!-- Problem diagram -->
            <div class="diagram-wrap">
                <div class="diagram-label">Problem: distributed state, no authority</div>
                <div class="prob-nodes">
                    <div class="prob-node normal">Checkout<strong>qty: 4</strong></div>
                    <div class="prob-node conflict">Warehouse<strong>qty: 2</strong></div>
                    <div class="prob-node normal">Returns<strong>qty: 5</strong></div>
                </div>
                <p class="prob-caption">Three services — three conflicting realities. No way to know which is right.</p>
            </div>

            <p>
                This is the split-brain problem. Each node believes its version is correct.
                Reconciling them requires either a painful merge strategy or an authoritative
                tiebreaker. SSOT is the architectural decision to declare that tiebreaker upfront,
                before any conflict happens.
            </p>

            <div class="pull-quote">
                "A system with two sources of truth has no source of truth."
            </div>

            <!-- Section 2 -->
            <h2>What SSOT actually means</h2>
            <p>
                The term is often used loosely. In the context of parallel system design, it has a
                precise meaning: <em>one canonical store owns each logical entity, and every other
                    representation is a derived projection of it.</em> Parallel consumers may hold local
                copies for performance, but those copies are always subordinate — caches, not authorities.
            </p>

            <!-- SSOT Architecture diagram -->
            <div class="diagram-wrap">
                <div class="diagram-label">SSOT architecture: one authority, many consumers</div>
                <div class="ssot-arch">
                    <div class="ssot-source-node">⬡ &nbsp; Authoritative Store — the SSOT</div>
                    <div class="ssot-arrow">
                        <div class="ssot-arrow-line"></div>
                        <div class="ssot-arrow-head"></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="ssot-consumers">
                        <div class="ssot-consumer">Service A<em>read replica</em></div>
                        <div class="ssot-consumer">Service B<em>event consumer</em></div>
                        <div class="ssot-consumer">Analytics<em>read projection</em></div>
                        <div class="ssot-consumer">Cache<em>evicted on write</em></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="section-accent"></div>

            <!-- Section 3 -->
            <h2>Core patterns for enforcing SSOT in parallel workloads</h2>
            <p>
                There is no single implementation. The right pattern depends on your consistency
                requirements, latency budget, and failure model. Here are four approaches that work
                in practice:
            </p>

            <div class="pattern-grid">
                <div class="pattern-card">
                    <div class="p-name">Optimistic Locking</div>
                    <div class="p-desc">Attach a version number to each record. Writers include the expected version;
                        the store rejects stale writes. Workers retry on conflict.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="pattern-card">
                    <div class="p-name">Event Sourcing</div>
                    <div class="p-desc">The event log is the SSOT. State is never stored directly — it's computed by
                        replaying the immutable append-only log.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="pattern-card">
                    <div class="p-name">Serializable Queues</div>
                    <div class="p-desc">Route all writes through an ordered queue. Workers consume sequentially,
                        preserving causal order without distributed locks.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="pattern-card">
                    <div class="p-name">CQRS</div>
                    <div class="p-desc">Separate the write model (commands → SSOT) from read models (projections).
                        Parallel reads never contend with writes.</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Optimistic locking in detail</h3>
            <p>
                Optimistic locking is the simplest entry point. Each row carries a <code>version</code>
                integer. A parallel worker reads the row — say, version 7 — does its computation, then
                issues an update conditional on the version still being 7. The database enforces atomicity.
                If another worker committed in the meantime, the version is now 8, the update fails with
                zero rows affected, and the worker retries with fresh data. No distributed coordination required.
            </p>
            <p>
                This works well when write conflicts are rare. When they are frequent — think hot-row
                contention on a shared counter — the retry storm can be worse than pessimistic locking.
                In those cases, consider partitioning the state so each parallel worker owns a disjoint
                shard, then merging results afterward.
            </p>

            <h3>Event sourcing as the ultimate SSOT</h3>
            <p>
                Event sourcing takes the idea further: the event log itself is the source of truth,
                not a derived state table. When multiple parallel workers emit events, the log captures
                them in order. Current state is always a fold over the log. This means no write ever
                destroys information — replaying from any checkpoint rebuilds the authoritative state.
            </p>
            <p>
                Parallel consumers can build their own read projections independently without any of
                them being "right" or "wrong" — they are all derived views of the same canonical log.
                The tradeoff is read latency and operational complexity. For systems that require full
                audit trails — financial ledgers, inventory, compliance workflows — the tradeoff is
                usually worth it.
            </p>

            <div class="section-accent"></div>

            <!-- Section 4: Consistency Spectrum -->
            <h2>The consistency spectrum</h2>
            <p>
                Not all systems can afford strong consistency. The SSOT principle does not require it.
                What it requires is that you are <em>explicit</em> about your consistency model, not
                accidental about it.
            </p>

            <table class="cons-table">
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Model</th>
                        <th>What parallel workers see</th>
                        <th>Latency</th>
                        <th>Suitable for</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Linearizable</strong></td>
                        <td>All writes globally ordered, immediately visible</td>
                        <td><span class="badge-lat badge-high">High</span></td>
                        <td>Financial transactions, inventory</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Serializable</strong></td>
                        <td>Transactions appear to execute one at a time</td>
                        <td><span class="badge-lat badge-medium">Medium</span></td>
                        <td>Booking systems, reservations</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Eventual</strong></td>
                        <td>Writes propagate asynchronously; stale reads possible</td>
                        <td><span class="badge-lat badge-low">Low</span></td>
                        <td>Social feeds, analytics, search indexes</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Causal</strong></td>
                        <td>Causally related writes seen in order; others may vary</td>
                        <td><span class="badge-lat badge-low">Low–Med</span></td>
                        <td>Collaborative editing, chat systems</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>

            <p>
                The critical point: every row in that table is compatible with SSOT. Even eventual
                consistency has a canonical store — it's just that reads may lag. The SSOT defines
                where truth lives; the consistency model defines how quickly that truth propagates
                to parallel consumers.
            </p>

            <div class="section-accent"></div>

            <!-- Section 5: Failure modes -->
            <h2>Common failure modes to design against</h2>

            <p>
                Even well-intentioned teams drift from SSOT over time. Watch for these:
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Dual-write without atomicity.</strong> A service writes to a database and
                publishes an event to a message bus in two separate operations. If the service crashes
                between the two, the bus and database diverge. Fix: use the transactional outbox pattern
                — write the event as a row in the same database transaction, then relay it asynchronously.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Cache that becomes the authority.</strong> A Redis cache is populated from the
                database. Then, under load, teams start writing to the cache directly because it's faster.
                The database is now stale, the cache is now the de facto SSOT, but it has no durability
                guarantee. Fix: never write to a cache that isn't backed by a write-through or
                write-around strategy tied to the authoritative store.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Microservice ownership creep.</strong> Service A owns the user entity. Service B
                needs a user field, so it stores a copy. Now both services own different fields of the same
                entity. Fix: establish clear domain ownership and expose data through APIs or events, never
                through direct shared tables.
            </p>

            <div class="pull-quote">
                Caches lie. Replicas lag. Event projections estimate. Only the SSOT is right — and only if you protect
                it.
            </div>

            <!-- Section 6: Checklist -->
            <h2>Practical checklist for a parallel system</h2>
            <p>Before shipping a parallel workload, run through these questions:</p>

            <div class="checklist-box">
                <div class="checklist-item">
                    <div class="check-icon">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 12 12">
                            <polyline points="2,6 5,9 10,3" />
                        </svg>
                    </div>
                    Is there exactly one store that owns each entity? Is it documented?
                </div>
                <div class="checklist-item">
                    <div class="check-icon">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 12 12">
                            <polyline points="2,6 5,9 10,3" />
                        </svg>
                    </div>
                    Do all writes go through the authoritative store before being projected elsewhere?
                </div>
                <div class="checklist-item">
                    <div class="check-icon">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 12 12">
                            <polyline points="2,6 5,9 10,3" />
                        </svg>
                    </div>
                    Have you chosen an explicit consistency model and designed retry/conflict logic around it?
                </div>
                <div class="checklist-item">
                    <div class="check-icon">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 12 12">
                            <polyline points="2,6 5,9 10,3" />
                        </svg>
                    </div>
                    Are cross-service writes atomic or protected by the transactional outbox pattern?
                </div>
                <div class="checklist-item">
                    <div class="check-icon">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 12 12">
                            <polyline points="2,6 5,9 10,3" />
                        </svg>
                    </div>
                    Is there an observable way to detect and alert when a derived store diverges from the SSOT?
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Closing -->
            <div class="closing-box">
                <h4>The bottom line</h4>
                <p>
                    Parallel execution is a performance strategy. SSOT is a correctness strategy. They are
                    not in conflict — the fastest parallel systems in production are the ones that invested
                    early in a clear authority model, because they spend zero cycles resolving contradictions
                    that should never have existed. Decide where truth lives, enforce it architecturally, and
                    let your workers run as fast as they want.
                </p>
            </div>

        </div><!-- /blog-body -->
    </article>
